DJ KARABO Mokanyane received an emotional send-off on Wednesday, 5 January. The award-winning artist, popularly known as Miss Ducasse, was described by friends and family as a prayer warrior who always spread love and positivity. The funeral service for Karabo, who died from complications following abdominal surgery on Wednesday, 29 December at the age of 41, took place at Grace Bible Church in Pimville, Soweto. Speaking at the funeral service, long-time friend Mputle Dikobe said Karabo enriched the lives of her friends. “This was done through her music and prayer. She lived a wonderful life and always surrounded herself with great people,” she said. “Although we are hurting because this loss has robbed us of a lot, we are also celebrating because she ran her race well.” Paying tribute to Karabo, DJ Lulo Cafe described her as warm and kind-hearted. “She became a sister to me and she taught me a lot of things. I will forever cherish the memories I shared with her,” he said. “She was kind and loving. Even at my lowest, she would always be there. It’s painful to say goodbye to her.” ALSO READ | MUSA MSELEKU PUTS THE BRAKES ON FIFTH WIFE Speaking on behalf of the family, Karabo’s brother Cambridge thanked everyone for their support. “Although it is hard, we shall forever cherish the memories. They will never be extinct in our hearts and mind,” he said. Karabo’s mum Sylvia said she was proud of the mark her daughter made. “She was an amazing person and we had a good relationship. We would always call each other and share jokes. I’m thankful for all the love you gave me and I will always love you,” she said.